,Recommended,289600,11790641,"Posted: 20 August, 2014",all,kschang77,"Marauder, aka ""Man of Prey"", can be best described as Jagged Alliance/Frozen Synapse  meets Homefront transplanted to Russia. You play Ahmed, a former Red Army soldier, now retired just trying to eek out a living. The local army have deserted in the face of advancing NATO ""peacekeepers"". As a ""marauder"", Ahmed will be looting the local warehouses, deal with any one who gets in his way, loot any useful items (including clothing, weapons, and other items that can be useful) sell and trade items, and basically survive and perhaps, find a way to get rid of the invaders.At its heart, Marauder is a turn-based tactical combat sim with simultaneous move phases. When not in combat, you may move about the map freely, looking for boxes to open or smash for loot inside (some locked boxes have to be forced). Enemies nearby triggers combat mode, where you plan your move, (kneel/crouch, aim this direction, hasty shot, for example) each of which takes a certain amount of time, and you only have so much in a single turn. Enemies will do the same. And if you manage to see each other, then they will shoot, and so on, based on complex combat formula such as weapon condition, relative movement, luck, and so on.The game is EXTREMELY difficult until you understand the combat mechanics, and how to setup ambushes properly so you take minimal damage (or none) in the combat phases, as well as knowing where the loot are. I think I have died about 15-20 times just in the end of the first mission (where you, with a shotgun and maybe a pistol, encounter three army deserters with pistols)  because I kept getting flanked or not doing the ambush right. But once you do, you felt as if you accomplished something.If you like your tactical games with a challenge, get Marauder (i.e. Man of Prey)."
,Recommended,289600,11213571,"Posted: 13 July, 2014",all,PAX_DOCTOR,"I loved this game! It adds up very entertaining tactical combat with original micromanagement system plus mature stalker-like setting. This mix formed a great gaming experience I haven't had in years. And I loved the main character being a selfish ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, not a filantropic savoiur angel, as is the expected cliché.The combat is challenging in the beginning. You have to get use to the system.(I strongly suggest to turn on HINTS option in the settings as it works like ingame tutorial). You will die from one shot across whole room while you will be more succesful throwing a rock rather than trying to shoot. Few missionst away, you will find yourself as battle-hardened killing machine raiding a military base full of badass gear. Bad idea to♥♥♥♥♥♥this marauder now.Some players are hating the graphics not looking cool and translation being bad. Message to you: This game is 5 years old and it's a miracle it even got released here on steam. The english translation was actually done by some Polish studio years after the game has beem released by different studio in Russia. Due to licencing issues there were no hard copies sold outside of Russia, until this (lucky) Steam release.Yep, it has some flaws - graphics settings like atialiasing don't work, you have to manualy fix the camera(look it up in the forums - it's pretty much worth the effort), and the game occasionaly crashes. BUT the main value lies in the cool combat system and the story with it's really original and entertaining characters and environment."
,Recommended,289600,11184869,"Posted: 11 July, 2014",all,Sex Brobot,"Everything I loved about Brigade E5, but with the bonus of a pretty solid story. The smart pause system is fantastic for tactical shenanigans, and the tons of equipment you can find, modify, and accessorize really makes the inventory management nerd in me happy. The RPG stats and picking ""perks"" when you gain a level is extra icing on this delicious cake for me.The translation is quite good, but has some of the typical weirdness associated with most Russian to English conversions (some of the introductions you make at the bazaar come off as abusive when I think they were shooting for casual). It's also a bit incomplete in places, but nothing that makes the game impossible to play (some NPC floating chats, markings of a few objectives on the map). Melee combat can be a little tricky as well. It's a little iffy if a PC will finish off a downed enemy with a quick boot, or will wiggle his arms around oddly, and getting stun locked is quite easy.The premise is pretty interesting, being a reverse Red Dawn\Post-Apocalyptic setting after a NATO occupation of Russia, where the area outside the major cities are left without government or basic infrastructure. This quickly leads to it being every man for himself, with all the fun that implies. Scavenging for canned food and medical supplies, fighting off warlords throwing their weight around, fortifying a old Soviet style apartment block, and building up a tight knit clan!All in all a game I enjoy the heck out of. Highly recommended."
